    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_507274610" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/507274610" />
    <a title="Grace Harwood" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16438199-grace-harwood"><img alt="Grace Harwood" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442658079p2/16438199.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/507274610?book_show_action=true">Jan 15, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Grace Harwood" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Grace Harwood" href="/user/show/16438199-grace-harwood">Grace Harwood</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer507274610" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8928950277010301493">When I first started writing,an editor advised me that a writer should always &quot;make every word work for its space in the manuscript; making every word count&quot;. I don&apos;t think I&apos;ve achieved it with every single word I&apos;ve ever written, probably not even in the one that&apos;s been published, but Charles Frazier does. Every single word counts towards making this one of the most beautiful, evocative historical novels I have ever read. The character I loved most was Waverley, Will&apos;s beloved horse. There is </span>
  <span id="freeText8928950277010301493" style="display:none">When I first started writing,an editor advised me that a writer should always "make every word work for its space in the manuscript; making every word count". I don't think I've achieved it with every single word I've ever written, probably not even in the one that's been published, but Charles Frazier does. Every single word counts towards making this one of the most beautiful, evocative historical novels I have ever read. The character I loved most was Waverley, Will's beloved horse. There is an element in Frazier's descriptions of the horse which echo the passage Will refers to in the story from the Bible, where God feels pride in the beauty of the World, "right down to the outward flare of the horse's nostril" (When Featherstone unlawfully gelds the animal, I wanted to string him up myself. I've never felt such anger on behalf of a fictional character before.) The story engaged me right from the beginning. I was powerless to look away from Will and Claire's love story. I was lost right from the opening paragraph to the closing one. The only words which don't make all that much sense to me in this story are the ones printed on the front cover of the book "Time fades everything. Except desire". Surely desire is the most transient and fleeting of all the emotions related to a great love. Still, this is a great story from a great writer. Don't miss it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8928950277010301493" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


