    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_28493982" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/28493982" />
    <a title="Julia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/339268-julia"><img alt="Julia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1223489302p2/339268.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/28493982?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julia" href="/user/show/339268-julia">Julia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9780739340462" href="/book/show/1523211.Thirteen_Moons">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Sad sacks, loney hearters, nostalgia fiends</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Julia by: </span>
      No one; I picked it up off the shelf
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer28493982" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5904570954558424373">This very long, very adjective-packed book is basically a study in heartbreak, and I would only reccommend it to those who like that sort of thing. The main character and narrator, one Will Cooper, has everything taken from him in his life, with the exception of money. That he seems to have a talent for accumulating (although in one chapter he looses that too, only to gain it again.) Everyone he loves is taken from him or voluntarily leaves, the homes that he knows don&apos;t hold any power over his </span>
  <span id="freeText5904570954558424373" style="display:none">This very long, very adjective-packed book is basically a study in heartbreak, and I would only reccommend it to those who like that sort of thing. The main character and narrator, one Will Cooper, has everything taken from him in his life, with the exception of money. That he seems to have a talent for accumulating (although in one chapter he looses that too, only to gain it again.) Everyone he loves is taken from him or voluntarily leaves, the homes that he knows don't hold any power over his roaming heart, and the country he loves is gradually destroyed by development. NOT TO MENTION, women, of course. To Will, women seems to be merely sexual recreation toys, no more--no less. His one great, all-consuming love, Claire, leaves him continually throughout the book, and his other amours don't stick around either for one reason or another. Claire is extremely poorly drawn for a main character, and the reader is left wondering as much about her when she takes her final leave, as when she shows up. If all this sounds like your kinda novel, by all means--go ahead and slog through it all. Me? I was left at the end with a sort of melancholy, unresolved, and lonely feeling that wasn't a joy to experience. And, I was left wondering what all the fuss had been about.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5904570954558424373" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


