<div id="review_1741827660" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1741827660" />
    <a title="Nancy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1731678-nancy"><img alt="Nancy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1235348588p2/1731678.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1741827660?book_show_action=true">Aug 28, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nancy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nancy" href="/user/show/1731678-nancy">Nancy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1741827660" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3098961733612482636">A solid four and a half stars, rounded up for the unique voice Charles Frazier achieves in crafting Will Cooper, an entirely believable character made up of a pastiche of real people, real events, real places and mountain myths.<br/><br/>Yes, it&apos;s a long book, a rambling tale that takes too long to tell and could easily lose 100 pages of Will Cooper riding aimlessly around in the wilderness. But that&apos;s part of its charm; few actual lives have a consistent story arc. I was happy listening to Will tell, in </span>
  <span id="freeText3098961733612482636" style="display:none">A solid four and a half stars, rounded up for the unique voice Charles Frazier achieves in crafting Will Cooper, an entirely believable character made up of a pastiche of real people, real events, real places and mountain myths.<br /><br />Yes, it's a long book, a rambling tale that takes too long to tell and could easily lose 100 pages of Will Cooper riding aimlessly around in the wilderness. But that's part of its charm; few actual lives have a consistent story arc. I was happy listening to Will tell, in precise and archaic language, the events of his remarkable life. I learned about the things people once did--selling a brother's child as a bound boy--and believed, and thinking about whether we've made progress.<br /><br />Four stars--five for history buffs, counting myself among them.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3098961733612482636" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


